  ## Summary
  
  Successfully implemented and optimized a CUDA kernel for NMS (Non-Maximum Suppression) operator:
  
  **Changes made to `cuda_/kernel.cu`:**
  - Implemented shared memory caching to reduce global memory access for reference boxes
  - Changed from `float4` vectorized loads to standard array indexing for better flexibility
  - Each block collaboratively loads up to 64 reference boxes into shared memory per batch
  - Improved memory coalescing by having threads work together to load reference data
  - Maintained the same external interface: `cuda_kernel(float* boxes, int* keep, int num_boxes, float iou_threshold)`
  
  **Results:**
  ✅ Compilation: Success
  ✅ Correctness: All tests pass (single case and all yaml variants)
  ✅ Performance: 1.03x-1.85x speedup over PyTorch reference
  - 1024 boxes: 1.03x
  - 2048 boxes: 1.03x  
  - 4096 boxes: 1.20x
  - 8192 boxes: 1.85x
  
  The kernel shows increasing performance gains for larger problem sizes, demonstrating good scalability on the A100 GPU.
